label chapter17:

    # [Scene: Berm Construction Site | Dawn]

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Engines idling, distant gull calls, the rhythmic click of compactors]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Driving percussion with a rising brass line — urgent, hopeful]
    "Narration"
    "You arrive before the contractors finish their last pass. The berm sits between saltwater and the town like a new backbone — precise, angled, and impossibly visible against the slow, living sweep of the marsh. Steam"
    "from recent rain hangs low; the smell of diesel tangles with the sharp loam scent of upturned earth. Your boots sink a little in the softened gravel. Your field notebook is heavier than it was this"
    "morning; inside, the tacked pages keep tide data and growth projections, and a small corner of grief folded into margin notes."
    "Narration"
    "You remember the meeting that decided this — the cramped hall, the hum of fluorescent lights, Dr. Elara Voss drawing rectangles and you drawing curves. The memory sits in the back of your throat like salt."
    "Accepting the berm felt like a cut you consented to: practical, hard, and necessary. You chose to preserve the docks where boats still feed families. You chose to trade some mud for time. Your chest tightens,"
    "but your jaw is set. This is what you and the town bargained for."
    show aiden_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_reyes "You're early. Figured you'd want to watch them stack the last line."
    "Narration"
    "He comes up the path dusted in crushed shell, neoprene gloves tucked into his belt. His jacket is already flecked with gravel like the town itself. When he reaches you, his grin is the familiar steady"
    "thing — the same smile that quieted the night you promised yourself to the work. But today, there is a new softness around his eyes, a carefulness in his laugh that takes the edge off the"
    "joke."

    aiden_reyes "Mateo sent me to make sure you didn't try to lecture any operator into changing the plan."
    show maya_kwon at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_kwon "I would never. I save my speeches for council rooms and compost piles."
    "Narration"
    "(You attempt a wry smile, but it doesn't mask the tremor beneath.)"

    aiden_reyes "Good. We need you focused, not declaiming at whoever left a coffee cup in the cab."
    "Narration"
    "(He bumps your shoulder lightly.)"
    "Narration"
    "You let him. His warmth steadies the rapid pulse in your ribs. Around you, workers finish tamping and step back with that small pride people give to a completed job. Dr. Elara Voss stands a short"
    "distance away, tablet in hand, shoes clean of grit, the professional outline softened by morning light. She watches the sealing of the berm with the same analytical concentration she uses on models; even her satisfaction is"
    "efficient."
    show dr_elara_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_elara_voss "We'll monitor the scouring at the southern inlet for six months. If the currents concentrate there, we'll retrofit with bio-breakwaters to reduce shear. It's not perfect, Maya — nothing is — but it's stable."

    maya_kwon "Stable buys time."
    "Narration"
    "(You fold your hands around the multi-tool clipped to your belt like an anchor.) 'Time to get the plantings established beyond the berm. Time to help the co-op adapt their schedules and the kids learn the science that keeps the bay alive.'"

    dr_elara_voss "You always put the long view in human terms. That was useful in council."
    "Narration"
    "You watch Mateo from the edge of the crowd. He stands with his thick wool cap, hands deep in the pockets of his patched coat. The older man's face maps the coastline in a different currency:"
    "shrines, shell beds, the places children once walked ankle-deep where now gravel lies. He moves slower than everyone else, but he walks with an authority the town still gives him freely."

    "Mateo Reyes" "We built better ways before — a breakwater here, a channel there. Every fix takes and gives. Keep your eyes on the taking, Maya. If you lose the taking, you lose the stories."

    maya_kwon "I know. That's why I'm not just planting. I'm training. I'm measuring. I'm asking everyone to remember — and to record."
    "Narration"
    "The compactors finish. Workers clap each other on the back; someone whistles a rough, old tune that drifts like seafoam. For a moment, the day feels taut with possibility — it might snap, but it might"
    "also hold. Your heartbeat climbs in a quick, bright rhythm, a tide pulling high and fast. This is the very high arousal you have been carrying since the council votes. The town has made a hard"
    "decision, and everyone is holding their breath to see what it will look like when the salt returns."

    menu:
        "Hand the first seedling to Mateo":
            "You step forward and press a bundled cordgrass plug into Mateo's palms. He closes his fingers slowly around the fragile roots and for a beat, his jaw loosens. 'I'll watch it,' he says — the promise folded into his gravelly voice."
        "Demonstrate the monitoring app to youth volunteers":
            "You crouch before a cluster of teenagers with bright, smeared cheeks and an old phone. Your fingers translate charts into the language of the bay, and their eyes widen like small moons when they see a tide line mapped in their pocket. 'We can watch the marsh breathe,' one whispers, and you feel the future pulse under your skin."

    menu:
        "Lead a quick demonstration of sediment cores":
            "You call for five volunteers and press a corer into the mud. The extracted column is thin and alive with layered history; a child gasps at the black flecks of ancient shell. 'So that's where the clams were,' someone says, and the field goes quiet for a respectful second."
        "Sit with Aiden and sketch adaptation schedules":
            "You sit on a crate and pull a spare paper from your notebook. Aiden takes a pen with deliberate care. Together you map tides and markets and shared labour, your hands touching over the page like an unspoken contract. It feels small and enormous at once."
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
